Class ClientProxy

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.hazelcast.client.spi.ClientProxy
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DistributedObject
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ClientAtomicLongProxy, ClientAtomicReferenceProxy, ClientCacheProxy, ClientCardinalityEstimatorProxy, ClientConditionProxy, ClientCountDownLatchProxy, ClientDurableExecutorServiceProxy, ClientExecutorServiceProxy, ClientFlakeIdGeneratorProxy, ClientIdGeneratorProxy, ClientListProxy, ClientLockProxy, ClientMapProxy, ClientMapReduceProxy, ClientMultiMapProxy, ClientPNCounterProxy, ClientQueueProxy, ClientReliableTopicProxy, ClientReplicatedMapProxy, ClientRingbufferProxy, ClientScheduledExecutorProxy, ClientScheduledFutureProxy, ClientSemaphoreProxy, ClientSetProxy, ClientTopicProxy, XAResourceProxy

    public abstract class ClientProxy
extends Object
implements DistributedObject
    Base class for client proxies.

    Allows the client to proxy operations through member nodes.

        public final String getName()
        Description copied from interface: DistributedObject
        Returns the unique name for this DistributedObject. The returned value will never be null. The suggested way for getting name is retrieving it through DistributedObjectUtil.getName(DistributedObject) because this might be also a PrefixedDistributedObject.
        Specified by:

      • getPartitionKey

        public String getPartitionKey()
        Description copied from interface: DistributedObject
        Returns the key of the partition that this DistributedObject is assigned to. The returned value only has meaning for a non-partitioned data structure like an IAtomicLong. For a partitioned data structure like an IMap, the returned value will not be null, but otherwise undefined.
        Specified by:
        getPartitionKey in interface DistributedObject

      • destroyLocally

        public final void destroyLocally()
        Destroys this client proxy instance locally without issuing distributed object destroy request to the cluster as the destroy() method does.

        The local destruction operation still may perform some communication with the cluster; for example, to unregister remote event subscriptions.

      • destroyRemotely

        public final void destroyRemotely()
        Destroys the remote distributed object counterpart of this proxy by issuing the destruction request to the cluster.
